description:
AD2016
A wardrobe staple reimagined. This long-sleeve button-down shirt from the Junya Watanabe Man line has some unique features. Key details include a front print of a face with no features but an eye, as well as an array of numbers and Russian? It seems that the print was heat pressed on, purposefully for too long, which left the darker box around the graphic. The print has some stitching detailing on top of it on both sides of the buttons. The shirt is made of multiple different striped cotton/nylon fabrics, three in total. The yoke has a red and blue polka dot pattern. Raw edges hang from where surging ended on the bottom hem, giving it a deconstructed finish.

(FOR SALE) A pair of Spring Summer 2009 Dolce & Gabbana â€˜Duneâ€™ Brown Multi-Pocket Flare-Zip Cargo Pants.
Dolce & Gabbanaâ€™s step into the new millennia was refreshing by all accounts. Introducing silhouettes akin to utility, the label immersed themselves under a militaristic persona. Popularized by designers like Helmut Lang, the tactical revolt provided a new take on utilitarian traditions. Incorporating luxury furs and expert tailoring, founders Stefano Gabbana and Domenico Dolce unapologetically pushed the envelope, straying far from their classic Italian roots. In the heat of the anti-fashion movement, experiment was encouraged and Gabbana embraced it. Using their power as an established Maison, the duo was able to create timeless staples, regarded as the brandâ€™s â€œgolden eraâ€.
This particular pair of cargo pants features many of the quintessential details that embody the ethos of D&Gâ€™s design. With an intricate seven pocket layout, these cargos feature button snap closures on the main compartments, allowing for more secure storage and ease of access. Continuing down to the bottom hem, these bottoms have the capability to flare outwards with matching rustic gold hardware. Coming in a size 31 waist, these pants are in pristine overall condition. Here is the opportunity to purchase a gorgeous pair of Dolce & gabbana cargo pants from a golden era of D&Gâ€™s legacy.

description:
Details
Dolce and Gabbana are considered the inventors of a Mediterranean style that draws its inspiration from the Sicily of Luchino Visconti's 1963 film The Leopard and the women of Italian realism, sensual and austere like Anna Magnani, to whom they dedicated a collection whose key element was the 1940s slip. At the beginning of their career, the designers also turned to Sophia Loren, Claudia Cardinale, and Stefania Sandrelli for inspiration. The Dolce & Gabbana woman is unbiased and brazen, but fearful of God and devoted to church and family, an attitude typical of southern Italian Catholicism. A woman who simultaneously reveals and conceals brassieres and corsets, lace, lingerie, and veils, and who is disturbing in her impetuous sensuality-a provocative woman proud of her body.
Boxy-fitting black military-style jacket that features translucent windows on various pockets on the front, the right sleeve, and the back, as well as a padded interior. The material strap attached to the collar allows it to be worn in many ways. Made in Italy.

description:
Dolce & Gabbanaâ€™s step into the new millennia was refreshing by all accounts. Introducing silhouettes akin to utility, the label immersed themselves under a militaristic persona. Popularized by designers like Helmut Lang, the tactical revolt provided a new take on utilitarian traditions. Incorporating luxury furs and expert tailoring, founders Stefano Gabbana and Domenico Dolce unapologetically pushed the envelope, straying far from their classic Italian roots. Using their power as an established maison, the duo was able to create timeless staples, regarded as the brandâ€™s â€œgolden eraâ€.

Debuting in the Spring of 2002, these militaristic bottoms exemplify Dolce & Gabbanaâ€™s push towards utility. White paint revolves around each leg, reading â€œDolce & Gabbanaâ€ in a faded hue. Complemented by reinforced seams, metallic paneling and a vast array of hardware, theyâ€™re finalized with 3D cargo pockets, and a wide cut. Stacking beautifully, these fit a 34x34, in great condition throughout.

description:
An Autumn Winter 2003 Dolce & Gabbana goggle military bomber jacket. Dolce & Gabbanaâ€™s golden age of utilitarian collections, spanning from Spring Summer 2003 and tapering off shortly after, are accredited for a mass adaptation of the ideology for luxury labels. Formerly seen as taboo to experiment with, Dolce & Gabbana was certainly not the first company to implement such into their work, but is undoubtedly one of the most influential.
One of the most iconic Dolce & Gabbana pieces from the Autumn Winter 2003 collection, this jacket was heavily inspired by American military aviation jackets. Featuring a goggle storage compartment on the left sleeve, cargo pocket detailing throughout and padded elbow patches, D&Gâ€™s infusion of practicality and tacticality work hand in hand cohesively. This piece is a size large and is in great overall condition. Here is the opportunity to purchase an incredible outerwear staple from Dolce & Gabbanaâ€™s legendary Autumn Winter 2003 collection.
The jacket is in great vintage condition. There is some wear on the see through parts which is inevitable, both from friction and the movement of these panels.
Labeled a size L. Measurements can be provided if necessary.
If you have any questions, feel free to PM me!

One of Japan's main creative forces in street-style, Hysteric Glamour is known primarily for their 60's iconography, love of punk and subversive prints. The label was founded by Nobuhiko "Nobu" Kitamura, whose love of the punk and new-wave scene dictated his design ethos. After graduating from Tokyo Mode Gakuen in 1984, Kitamura went on to pursue fashion, finding a part-time job at Ozone Community, a youth-oriented label that was cresting as Japanese fashion steered more towards directional silhouettes. After a few years at Ozone Community Kitamura founded Hysteric Glamour, adapting the aesthetics of Andy Warhol and the new-wave scene and bringing them to the forefront of Japanese fashion. Reminiscent of retro bowling lane uniforms this black shirt features a spread collar with a loop button closure. A "Hysteric" embroidery accents the right chest pocket, white stitching contrasts the sleeves and a "Hysteric Times" graphic is printed on the back of the garment.

KAPITAL Century Monkey Cisco â€œMudâ€ Denim No.9+S.
*** NEW SEASON VERSION/ NEW SEASON BACK TABS***
Color: Black (with naturally mud dyedâ€” brown linen sashiko stitches all throughout).
Size: 34 (fits a size 32 waist).
Straight fit.
Woven on customised looms in Hiroshima.
The fabric is spun using naturally Yeddo Hawthorn Trees and mud dyed cotton and linen threads.
Mud dyeing is a time-honoured dyeing technique native to Japan's Amami Oshima islands.
The unique, iron rich mud of Amami Oshima results in the beautiful deep black brown shade reflected in these jeans.
Made in Japan.
In Depth Details About The Dye:
The wood chips from locally grown Yeddo Hawthorn trees are boiled. The remaining dye bath rests for a week to prepare for a deep brown dye.
The yarn is dyed first in this tannin-rich dye bath.
This prepared yarn is then dipped in a mud pit. The chemical reaction between tannin from the Yeddo Hawthorn tree and iron from mud turns the yarn color to the â€œcolor of the earthâ€.
Mordanting hanks of yarn in mud. The color changes to an earthy black.
This process is repeated by hand for about 30 times to achieve the color of Century Denim.
Original booklet included.
81% Cotton, 19% Linen. 
Ships from Japan within 2-3 days of purchase.

Kapital began as a family owned denim manufacturing venture located in Kojima, which is known as the â€œDenim Capital of Japan.â€ Currently their mainline branch is known for their whimsical graphic-centric output. This Smiley Face motif is one of their quintessential creations, and it clearly defines the brandâ€™s affection for Hippy Modernism. This specific piece takes a minimalist approach to the application of the motif, as the artwork was simply printed on the elbows of the garment, which leaves an abundance of negative space all around it. The structure of the garment is reminiscent of the 1960â€™s with itâ€™s slightly miss-registered screenprint, textured mid-weight jersey cotton, and a generally relaxed fit with dropped shoulders.

One of the most sought after names in the world of denim, Kapital hail from the jean capital of Japan, the city of Kurashikiâ€™s portside Kojima district. Originally a sewing and dyeing factory that produced product for other companies, Kapital parlayed their years of hard won expertise into their own signature label, launched in 1996.
Kapital marries impeccable craftsmanship and innovative textile technique with an intricately detailed, elegantly offbeat signature look, creating some of the most unique, and widely coveted items in the world.
1st jacket made of flannel fabric. The processing technology faithfully reproduces the fading and texture of the vintage bandana with flannel fabric and raises it to create a pop patchwork pattern. It is reversible with double-sided printing, so you can enjoy it according to your mood.

description:
Intended to purchase as a gift, did not go through
Also not my size so never worn
Purchase in May 2022.
Size 36
Includes free tote bag from Blue In Green NY
This is the denim for indigo-obsessives. 3 types of indigo go into making these jeans: American Indigo (No. 1, in Kapital's lingo), Japanese Indigo (No. 2), and Natural Indigo (No. 3). Each of the yarns - warp, weft, and sashiko - are rope-dyed with one indigo for maximum fading potential.
The weaving process to create this denim is a trade secret with Kapital - it all goes through one loom, and one loom only. The base denim in this case is a bit slubbier than the other Century denims, and it's all sewn up in the new Monkey Cisco fit.
The Monkey fit is an update to the original Cisco fit. The rise is higher, the seat and thighs are fuller, and there's a slight taper below the knee. These will still fit over a pair of boots comfortably.
These are true to tag size, so one size up from your US denim size; double check the size chart for details. Minimal shrink is expected, and will be recovered when they stretch post-wash.
We suggest 2 soaks inside out to knock out some of the initial crocking, as these will turn you and everything you love blue. Try to avoid machine washing for the first year or so, as well.
100% cotton proprietary sashiko denim
3 shades of indigo
Runs small, size up
Cold soak, hang dry
Made in Japan

Brand New/ Never Worn.
KAPITAL Century Monkey Cisco â€œMudâ€ Denim No.9+S.
Color: Black (with naturally mud dyedâ€” brown linen sashiko stitches all throughout).
Size: 36 (fits a size 34 waist).
Straight fit. Taper leg.
Woven on customised looms in Hiroshima.
The fabric is spun using naturally Yeddo Hawthorn Trees and mud dyed cotton and linen threads.
Mud dyeing is a time-honoured dyeing technique native to Japan's Amami Oshima islands.
The unique, iron rich mud of Amami Oshima results in the beautiful deep black brown shade reflected in these jeans.
Made in Japan.
In Depth Details About The Dye:
The wood chips from locally grown Yeddo Hawthorn trees are boiled. The remaining dye bath rests for a week to prepare for a deep brown dye.
The yarn is dyed first in this tannin-rich dye bath.
This prepared yarn is then dipped in a mud pit. The chemical reaction between tannin from the Yeddo Hawthorn tree and iron from mud turns the yarn color to the â€œcolor of the earthâ€.
Mordanting hanks of yarn in mud. The color changes to an earthy black.
This process is repeated by hand for about 30 times to achieve the color of Century Denim.
Original booklet included.
81% Cotton, 19% Linen. 
Ships from Japan within 2-3 days of purchase.

KAPITAL Century Monkey Cisco â€œMudâ€ Denim No.9+S.
Color: Black (with naturally mud dyedâ€” brown linen sashiko stitches all throughout).
Size: 36 (fits a size 34 waist).
Straight fit. Taper leg.
Woven on customised looms in Hiroshima.
The fabric is spun using naturally Yeddo Hawthorn Trees and mud dyed cotton and linen threads.
Mud dyeing is a time-honoured dyeing technique native to Japan's Amami Oshima islands.
The unique, iron rich mud of Amami Oshima results in the beautiful deep black brown shade reflected in these jeans.
Made in Japan.
In Depth Details About The Dye:
The wood chips from locally grown Yeddo Hawthorn trees are boiled. The remaining dye bath rests for a week to prepare for a deep brown dye.
The yarn is dyed first in this tannin-rich dye bath.
This prepared yarn is then dipped in a mud pit. The chemical reaction between tannin from the Yeddo Hawthorn tree and iron from mud turns the yarn color to the â€œcolor of the earthâ€.
Mordanting hanks of yarn in mud. The color changes to an earthy black.
This process is repeated by hand for about 30 times to achieve the color of Century Denim.
Original booklet included.
81% Cotton, 19% Linen. 
Ships from Japan within 2-3 days of purchase.

description:
Design concept of KAPITAL is the fusion of the West and Japan. EAST MEETS WEST, a blend of Japanese and Western styles.
KAPITAL was founded in Kojima, Okayama, the birthplace of Japan Denim. The company set up a sewing factory to produce jeans under a famous brand. In 1996, in order to express their own concept, they launched their own brand, KAPITAL and began producing the first model of jeans. By the way, the jeans are still produced and sold. The company's name was firstly CAPITAL when they started, but when the first shop was opened in a different location from the head office, they changed the brand and shop name from "CAPITAL" to "KAPITAL" to avoid a confusion with other shops having the same name.
KAPITAL started with the production of jeans, but now they produce many items, mainly denim wear. With the exception of a few items such as shoes and accessories, all of KAPITAL items are made in KAPITAL own factories. A few years ago, KAPITAL aquired a factory that carries out the wash and has been doing all the washing and processing that characterize KAPITAL products today.
Processing and sewing are KAPITAL's strength. KAPITAL craftpersons sew denim with a conscious of processing. There are still few brands in the world that can do both sewing and processing.
